Sr. my last to you was on the 23: curitt sence recd yd of 15: ditto as to the bayes
they are very deare in the north where fore wee may desist yett a while
though I doubt I shall want a hundred peeces be fore winter: I have qve
you credits for my halfe share in the reds aboard Ben: Clarck & in the
northrens aboardpindar. I thought my ordr for northen goods was
formerly compleated, yett hope this bale will prove to content
the aurooas are to deare, therefore
God sone all safe to arrive
you did well to send non for wee must studdy to gaine & not to loose:
I take not ice what you did concerneng trade others of this towne
when I see you, I hope to give you good satisfaction there in, as also
in the continuation of our trade, thougst doubt less the 3 necees whare
houses in cloth will do us preiudice of that more when see you i
hath seen very de ad of late for mony which I hope is over I am ring
to brussels and de endeavour to remitt you £1000: which I exspect
to performe in cevery short time ou which you may depend & for yd
commodation, shall remitt what is for my acctt. ast short sight &
for yd att 2 uso & so remaine with kinde salato
@ 30 d itto
London Abramvivian
h
Sr. sence my last to you of 23 curitt reseaved yd of 11 & 15 ditto in
the first you advise mee the lading of 6 bales withent notn n
what vessel thought I supose itt is aboard pindar because you said
that nelson lyds out for london & yett in yd latters itt I coms t hat
the goods ard avoard of nelson: I could wish you did send mee the bill of
loading of what goods soever you shipt, for you can have 2 bill one of them
for eee o the other for yd selfa I supose that mr. potter shall exceed us. pareson
in all respects for as much as yett I can learne, besides itt will be casies for
you asso to keep to one onely: as to the last bayes they ares good for them
prijses, and well bought, butt the 2 that are less is a great mistake & I have
examined them over & over againe my self so that what I woott you is realy
so I could wish to have a houndred bayes more for the prijses, so in case yd siend
could provide some marcks cas I should advise for the: same prijses, I shoud
be content where fore informe yd self concerning the same for shall
want more bayes before winter I am sorry to see that the laces prove
not to yd minde & yett others do not complaine, so do not know where
the case byes yo want more mony, I a sorry that I can not provide
you with what you desire up on demand for wee have hadd a mightly ded
time of late in mony, so that I have don all I could hetherto & shall
endeavour further to suply you whilst now I remaine
Antw: 30 July
London George Cole
h
S in answer to yd of 8: curitt I can assure you that payment is vere badd here
& worse then ever itt was yett so that I could wish you was here butt he kalf
an how & I should be able to give you such content that I doubt not butt you
should answer to satis fartion, tot lose that are so mguiring after mee
I do assure you I make no use of that mony, butt endeavour all I can
to cleare that acctt. for I do not love to be scrupeled inclosed you have
mj bill for £70: on mr. Henry Collier att 2uso for which please to give
mee creditt att 35:5: I shall do all I can to remitt more S. first intrim
receave no letters from mr. D. vivian I desire you to hefp mee to my
mony & so remaine with kend saluto
@ 30 July
London Henty collier
S. in answer to yd of 8 & 15 curitt I have accepted yd bill for £100: & yeasterday
payd the £30:- att 35:6: to william powell for francus forsterd as you
ast, I have also examined yd acctt. and find that itt is
ordered mee the 17
rmpossible to cleare the last acctt. yett for the payement are worse then
evertley were, besides of the debts transported by the idow boels doth
not come in one penny, & yett I am charges ther a with up on yd acctt
I assure you that I do not love to complaine and could wish to reture
yd mony to yd owne content, butt as things now, gothose is no hopes to
tradeis brought low & mony extreamly seare there by the countrey
men aeld aghine with warr & itt can herdely fus sist without itt
I must remitt mr. Anneslay £50: & mr George Cole £70: so have send
them my bills on you att 2 uso att 35:5: & that I could not avoid for have
no monyes in cash, so please to accept them & note accordingly I take
notice you bought 20 cottons, please to dispatch them for they ought
to be here in short time: tis good you sold the returned cloathes they: will
have yalded much more with you then ever I should have been able to mak
off here: as to the concernig of m.TH. I hope the in large p nett whilst

Sr. my last to you was on the 16: curitt sence non from you inclosed £50
on mr. Henry Collier of yd acctt in my owne bill att 35: 5 more p next
intrim. I have recd our 4 bales come by thom Elsdon the serges prove
indifferent well, butt the whate perpetunness are extrauagant d'eare & not
by 518 apr worth their price, I have sold 42 serpes which will render about
9 p. proffitt & hope to make as much of the rest: John Ewings
me and wils is arrived from Eion, butt I do not perceave that our last goods
are aboard, of him which I could have wished, for do much want them
inclosed you have the pattarnes of the bale N.16 accordingly to which
please to order mr. wood to provide one bale of 25 cloth serves more a to
dispatch the one & the other as soone as possible &to endeavour for good
goods pray tell him that the goods must be some what more prest then
these last have been in so much that they may have a shire of acolandes
& lett him bestow 26 to 50 a peeces which is recommanded to yd
cure whilst
